The Large Hadron Collider (LHC) is anticipated to generate new particles during its Run II phase, including potential discoveries beyond the Standard Model through processes such as b → sγ or t → cZ decays. The Belle experiment has recently explored these phenomena with unprecedented precision, providing valuable experimental insights into models that suggest deviations from Standard Model predictions. In this presentation, I will provide an overview of recent results from Belle that focus on distinguishing decay modes involving charm quarks. This will include measurements of: 
- Branching fractions for charmless hadronic B meson decays; 
- Decay asymmetries in neutral D mesons produced from B meson decays; 
- Branching fractions for Bc → J/ψX decays. 
I will also discuss how these findings can help constrain extensions of the Standard Model. Finally, I will outline some future plans for Belle experiments.

We conducted predictions regarding the formation of pulsars (PSRs) based on various parameters and periods associated with their platforms. We utilized Monte Carlo simulations to analyze the evolution of binary and triple systems, drawing on data from observations of relevant clusters. Our population synthesis was carried out using our code designed for simulating close binary systems, along with a separate code for modeling the dynamical interactions within stellar systems. Our findings indicate that most PSRs are more likely to be part of hierarchical triples rather than isolated systems or simple binaries. Specifically, we found that: 
- Most PSRs are expected to have companion masses ranging from 0.1 to 1.0 solar masses; 
- Most PSRs are likely to orbit with semi-major axes of less than 100 AU; 
- Most PSRs will not transition into millisecond pulsars prior to their first supernova explosion; 
- Most PSRs will experience significant gravitational wave emission throughout their lifetimes.
